<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-673-193  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 673 193.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 10 1990 v7 n49 p33(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hi Tech unveils employee-evaluation package. (Hi Tech Enterprisesintroduces Employee Evaluator and Salary Manager software)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Hi Tech Enterprises introduces Employee Evaluator and SalaryManager, a software package designed to streamline and standardizeworker evaluations and salary reviews.andP;  It helps managers rateemployees objectively according to standard criteria, avoidingcharges of favoritism and possible wrongful-termination lawsuits.andO;The package also documents ratings if the company does need todefend itself in court.andP;  Employee Evaluator and Salary Managerlets users incorporate categories such as customer relations,attendance and time management and rate how employees perform ineach category on a percentile scale.andP;  The user can assign a seriesof custom-written questions to each category.andP;  Hi Tech offers thebasic package with unlabeled categories starting at $290; versionswith labeled default categories that can be customized areavailable at extra cost.andP;  The package runs on DOS, OS/2 and IBM4680 systems.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hi Tech Enterprises (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Employee Evaluator and Salary Manager (Computer program) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Personnel managementSoftware packagesEmployee.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;Hi Tech Enterprises has released a program that promises to provide asolution for managers trying to streamline and standardize employeeevaluations and salary raises.andM;Available now, the Employee Evaluator andamp; Salary Manager is designed to allowmanagers to rate employee performance and objectively determine salaryincreases, according to officials at the Monterey, Calif., company.andM;The software package also helps employers define companywide goals, thusavoiding charges of favoritism and the possible resulting lawsuits, earlyusers of the program said.andM;&quot;Employee Evaluator helps an employer objectively rate employees according tostandard criteria,&quot; said Dennis McKane, president of McKane's CenturionSecurity and Investigations in San Jose, Calif.andP;  &quot;It also documents theratings in case an employee charges the employer with wrongful termination.&quot;andM;The software allows users to incorporate categories -- such as timemanagement, attendance and customer relations -- on which each employeeshould be rated.andP;  The basic package comes with unlabeled categories; for anadditional cost, the software can be delivered with default categories thatare labeled already but can be customized.andM;After determining what categories employees are to be evaluated on, usersassign a number that determines the relative weight categories will have onthe overall evaluation.andM;The program also lets users rate how employees are performing in eachcategory on a scale of 0 percent to 100 percent.andP;  To objectively guide theevaluation, the user can write a series of questions and assign them to eachcategory.andM;In the customer-relations category, for example, the software can ask whethera salesperson has repeat customers.andM;Once all ratings have been completed, the software automatically calculatesthe employee's total score as a percentage, taking both employees' ratingsand each category's relative weight into account.andP;  Salary increases arelinked to these overall scores.andM;For example, the package can be programmed to assign a 25 percent raise toemployees scoring between 60 percent and 100 percent.andP;  If budgetaryconstraints do not allow the salary increases, the software will apportionavailable funds.andM;Prices for Employee Evaluator, which runs on DOS, OS/2 and IBM 4680 systems,starts at $290.andM;Hi Tech Enterprises can be reached at (408) 373-5117.andO;</TEXT></DOC>